tion test flow: creating a match, verifying the database state, simulating a join with a locked account response, running the worker to detect and settle the match, then confirming the final settled state with the secret and verification data. Now I need to construct the mock account data by understanding the CoinflipMatch layout—the discriminator takes the first 8 bytes, followed by creator and opponent public keys, and I'll need to map out the remaining fields to build realistic test data. Looking at the byte layout more carefully, I need to verify the field offsets against the actual struct definition from state.rs to make sure my calculations are correct. Now I'm mapping out the exact byte offsets for each field in the account structure, starting from the 8-byte discriminator and working through all the fields to verify the total size aligns with my calculation. Now I'm verifying the CoinflipConfig struct layout with the treasury offset at 40 bytes. I need to set up the test infrastructure—mocking the Connection class, building account data for a locked match state, creating config and entropy accounts, and wiring everything into the Hono app. I also need to handle request signing with Ed25519 signatures since the auth middleware validates them, though I'll need to work around Hono's body-reading limitation.\n\nWriting the integration test... I see the issue now — the backend modules expect a typed `Connection` parameter from the Solana library, so I can't just pass a mock object without TypeScript complaining. I'll need to use a type assertion like `as unknown as Connection` to make the test work, since the actual `Connection` class requires real network setup that I don't want in a unit test.\n\nLooking at the dependency interfaces, they all expect `Connection` from `@solana/web3.js`, so I need to create a mock that implements the methods the code actually calls and then cast it appropriately.\n\nFor the test flow, I'm setting up keypairs for the server, creator, opponent, and treasury, then creating a mock Connection with state tracking. I'll connect to a real Postgres instance, run migrations, initialize the Hono app with routes and middleware, and set up the settlement worker with the mock Connection. Then I'll walk through the full lifecycle: signing a create request with the creator's keypair, posting to the endpoint, verifying the response includes the transaction and match PDA, checking that the database records the round in the created phase, and simulating the join by updating the mock Connection's state.\n\nFrom there, I'll trigger the worker's poll method to transition to locked state, update the mock to report that the current slot has reached the target, mock the settle transaction handling, and call poll again to verify the database transitions to settled with the result data. Finally, I'll fetch the round details and verify the response includes the secret, result hash, result side, winner, and verification object before cleaning up the database.\n\nThe tricky part is implementing the mock Connection correctly—I need to handle `getLatestBlockhash()` returning the blockhash and last valid block height, and `getSlot()` for the worker's polling logic.\n\nBuilding the MockConnection class... Setting up test imports...\n\nNow I'm deciding whether to use a real database or mock it for these tests—that'll affect how I structure the test setup. Building the mock Connection class... Continuing with the account filtering logic...\n\nNow I'm implementing the remaining RPC methods—returning account info with the standard Solana account structure, generating a fake transaction signature for raw transactions, confirming transactions with a mock slot, and providing a default balance of 2 SOL for any account query.\n\nAdding test helper methods...\n\nI'm realizing there's a mismatch in how the mock handles the `getProgramAccounts` filters—the actual backend code uses base58 encoding for the bytes field in memcmp filters, but I need to make sure my mock decodes those properly to match the settlement worker's expectations.\n\nBuilding mock account data... Writing the serialization logic... Writing buffer construction functions...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the test flow more carefully. For the POST endpoint, I need to create a valid auth signature and send the request, which will trigger `buildCreateMatchTx` to fetch the latest blockhash and return a partial transaction. Then I'll query the rounds table to verify the round is in the created phase, and after that I need to update the mock Connection to return the match account in a locked state for the join simulation.\n\nI'll extract the commitment and match PDA from the POST response, then have the worker poll to detect the locked match—it should call `getProgramAccounts()`, identify it as new, transition the DB from created to locked, and log the event. The worker will also check if the target slot is reached to trigger settlement, which involves fetching the secret from the database and retrieving the match and config account data.\n\nAfter building and signing the settle transaction, I'll send it and confirm it, then update the DB to settled. I can verify the round is now settled with the result data, and finally call the GET endpoint to confirm all expected fields are present. I'm thinking through how to handle the `settleMatch` function being called from `onSettleReady` within the worker's poll method—for the integration test, I can simplify by calling it directly rather than going through the retry wrapper.\n\nActually, I should use the retry settler to match how the real app works. I also need to mock the `entropyAccount` config since the real app defaults to the SlotHashes sysvar, and I'll need to set up mock account data for the test. The worker's poll loop will discover matches and trigger `onSettleReady`, and with the retry settler in place, it should handle the happy path on the first attempt since it tracks failed PDAs and won't retry after max retries. There's a potential issue though—the DB transitions from \"locked\" → \"settling\" → \"settled\" during `settleMatch`, so I need to make sure the state transitions work correctly through the poll cycle.\n\nOn the next poll, the match account will still exist in the mock unless I explicitly remove it, but that's actually fine for the test. The retry settler's `attemptSettle` doesn't check if a match is already settled, so I need to verify how it handles that case—whether it tracks the PDA as failed or if the DB phase being \"settled\" causes an error that prevents re-settlement.\n\nFor the mock, I think the simplest approach is to just call poll once after setting up the LOCKED state and confirming the target slot is reached, then verify the results without worrying about account cleanup or retry logic.\n\nLooking at the poll implementation, it awaits the `onSettleReady` callback, so when I call `await worker.poll()`, the entire settlement flow completes before returning. When poll discovers the match for the first time with the target slot already reached, it adds the PDA to discovered matches, fetches the phase from the database (which is \"created\"), transitions it to \"locked\", and logs the event.\n\nThen in the same cycle, it checks the target slot, finds it's been reached, and triggers the settlement callback. Since the phase was just transitioned to \"locked\", the settle function should proceed correctly through its full sequence: fetching the round, transitioning to \"settling\", logging the submission, fetching the necessary accounts, pre-computing the result, building and signing the transaction, sending it, and confirming it before the final phase transition.\n\nNow I'm looking at how the retry settler wrapper handles this—it has its own checks before attempting settlement, including verifying the resolve deadline hasn't passed by reading from the account at a specific offset.\n\nSince I set the deadline 24 hours in the future, that should pass the check, but I need to make sure the mock is configured to return the match account data when `getAccountInfo` is called, not just when `getProgramAccounts` queries it.\n\nI'll refactor the mock to use a single internal map of accounts that both methods can access, so I don't have to maintain separate data stores.\n\nRefactoring the mock connection... Writing filter logic... Setting up test imports...\n\nI need to check the retry settler's dependency interface to understand what parameters it expects when initialized, so I can wire everything together correctly in the test setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2457,"cache_read_input_tokens":78624,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2457},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"571f6196-8768-4189-b912-c43475f582e6","uuid":"3d446dd1-a2f2-4a5d-903b-0d28db824c21"}
